<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-03T12:41:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-03T12:41:00-05:00" n="907" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d907">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/407</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-03T19:00:00+01:19">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 4, 9.41 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2452. My 2426, April 29, 5 p.m. The Minister for Foreign Affairs has just
                            told me that the negotiations with Germany seem nearly to have reached
                            an agreement in the sense of the statement sent you in the above
                            telegram, that is to say: <list>
                                <label>1. (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                                <item>Germany has agreed to the limit of 1,600,000 tons per annum
                                    and will give an undertaking that this will not be used for
                                    military purposes.</item>
                                <label/>
                                <item>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) 250,000 tons per month is
                                    recognized as a maximum that will probably never be reached. As
                                    to the exchange for coal and iron that does not seem to enter in
                                    at the moment.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>Agreed to as to the ships at Antwerp.</item>
                                <label>3.</label>
                                <item>Agreed to except that there is not yet an understanding as to
                                    what constitutes military “arms”.</item>
                                <label>4.</label>
                                <item>Agreed to.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> professes
                            to believe that the final agreement will be reached.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>